<subSubSection id="C3116537A029FB7B988BFE69FD2DFCE2" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB436BCA029FB7B988BFE69FD2DFCE2" blockId="2.[151,1437,362,1504]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">
Description: Head globular, partly hidden in pronotum. Rostrum short and stout, bent downwards and straight (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B98D3FE55FF6CFE52" box="[159,225,434,460]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Figs 1</figureCitation>
A-D). In dorsal view widening anteriad. Eyes oval, larger than width of rostrum at base and weakly protruding from outline of head (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B998CFE31FD8CFE6E" box="[448,513,470,496]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
D). Antennae with six funicular segments, second segment partly hidden in first. Club oval, large, as long as funicular segments together (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9B6FFE1DFCEAFD8A" box="[803,871,506,532]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
H). Prothorax cylindrical, constricted before front and hind margins (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9920FDF9FE20FDA6" box="[364,429,542,568]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A). Front margin of prothorax in ventral view angularly emarginate (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9C8CFDF9FA8DFDA6" box="[1216,1280,542,568]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
B). In ventral view, both, front and hind margins of prothorax with fringes of appressed, scale-like bristles (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9CF0FDA5FB70FDC2" box="[1212,1277,578,604]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
B). Scutellum pentagonal. Elytra wider than prothorax with prominent shoulders, hind wings present. Elytra with ten striae, stria 10 shortened and bent into 9 after first third of elytral length. Striae with coarse punctation, intervals of same width, weakly vaulted. Inner side of elytra at apex without stridulatory ridges. Prothorax and elytra with weakly bowed, adjacent and long and clubbed scales. Venter with procoxae separated by one third of coxal diameter, metacoxae separated by half coxal diameter and metacoxae separated by little more than diameter of a coxa (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9C9AFD11FA98FC8E" box="[1238,1301,758,784]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
B). All ventrites with sutures clearly visible (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9A5BFCFDFDDAFCAA" box="[535,599,794,820]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
G). Legs stout all femora with femoral tooth (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9C2CFCFDFB29FCAA" box="[1120,1188,794,820]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Figs 1</figureCitation>
J-K). Tibiae uncinate, premucro present. Tarsi with bilobed third tarsomere, claws free. Male genitalia with large tegminal plate, short lobes and long tegminal apodeme (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9A52FC85FDECFCE2" box="[542,609,866,892]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Figs 1</figureCitation>
E-F).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3116537A029FB7B988BFC61FD51FC76" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB436BCA029FB7B988BFC61FD51FC76" blockId="2.[151,1437,362,1504]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">
Derivation of name: The genus name is an anagram of the name 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9BDDFC61FB15FC3E" authority="Germar, 1817" authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[913,1176,902,928]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hylobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9BDDFC61FC7BFC3E" box="[913,1014,902,928]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Hylobius</emphasis>
Germar, 1817
</taxonomicName>
, a well known genus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B98DBFC4DFE9EFC5A" authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="1865" baseAuthorityName="Kirby" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[151,275,938,964]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Hylobiinae">Hylobiinae</taxonomicName>
in the Palaearctic and Nearctic Regions. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9A92FC4DFC4FFC5A" authority="Germann, 2021" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2021" box="[734,962,938,964]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Obhylius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arboricola" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9A92FC4DFC4FFC5A" box="[734,962,938,964]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Obhylius arboricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A24C57D5A029FB7B9B85FC4DFB92FC5A" box="[969,1055,938,964]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar in its habitus and shares some characters with this genus. Gender masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3116537A029FB7B988BFC15FAF9FA7E" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BB436BCA029FB7B988BFC15FAA0FA22" blockId="2.[151,1437,362,1504]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">
Remarks: Anew genus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B99BEFC15FDE8FB92" authorityName="Schoenherr" authorityYear="1823" box="[498,613,1010,1036]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Molytinae">Molytinae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9A39FC15FC97FB93" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[629,794,1010,1037]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Curculionidae</taxonomicName>
), here assigned to the tribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9C1CFC15FB37FB92" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2021" box="[1104,1210,1010,1036]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pissodini">Pissodini</taxonomicName>
, subtribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9D64FC15FF7DFBAE" authorityName="Morimoto" authorityYear="1962" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Cotasteromimina">Cotasteromimina</taxonomicName>
. It shares the characters originally proposed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A4B4DA029FB7B9B4CFBF1FC5EFBAF" author="Morimoto, K." box="[768,979,1046,1073]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" pagination="21 - 66" refId="ref4836" refString="Morimoto, K. (1962 b) Key to families, subfamilies, tribes and genera of the superfamily Curculionoidea of Japan excluding Scolytidae, Platypodidae and Cossoninae. (Comparative morphology, phylogeny and systematics of the superfamily Curculionoidea of Japan. III). Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Kyushu University, 12, 21 - 66. https: // doi. org / 10.5109 / 22693" type="journal article" year="1962">Morimoto (1962b)</bibRefCitation>
, and redescribed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A4B4DA029FB7B9CFAFBF1FEA3FBCA" author="Germann, C. &amp; Grebennikov, V." pageId="2" pageNumber="569" pagination="197 - 211" refId="ref4366" refString="Germann, C. &amp; Grebennikov, V. (2020) A new weevil genus from the highlands of China casts doubts on monophyly of Cotasteromimina (Coleoptera: Curculionidae, Molytinae). Fragmenta Entomologica, 52 (2), 197 - 211. https: // doi. org / 10.4081 / fe. 2020.459" type="journal article" year="2020">Germann &amp; Grebennikov (2020)</bibRefCitation>
: 1.) abdominal process between hind coxae much broader than the coxal width; 2.) robust rostrum, relatively short and not more than 1.1x longer than pronotal length; 3.) eyes in lateral view closely approximate to front margin of pronotum, width of temples less than the diameter of the eye. Furthermore, the raised scales on the elytra (as long as distance between intervals), and the peculiar character of the second segment of the antennal funiculus hidden inside the first one, are characters shared with 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9B7FFB2DFC69FB7A" authority="Morimoto, 1962" authorityName="K.Morimoto" authorityYear="1962" baseAuthorityName="Morimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[819,996,1226,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudohylobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9B7FFB2DFC69FB7A" box="[819,996,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Pseudohylobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF9A4B4DA029FB7B9BBFFB2DFB35FB7B" author="Morimoto, K." box="[1011,1208,1226,1253]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" pagination="375 - 407" refId="ref4768" refString="Morimoto, K. (1962 a) Descriptions of a new subfamily, new genera and species of the family Curculionidae of Japan. (Comparative morphology, phylogeny and systematics of the superfamily Curculionoidea of Japan. II). Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Kyushu University, 11, 375 - 407. https: // doi. org / 10.5109 / 22691" type="journal article" year="1962">Morimoto 1962a</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9CA7FB2DFA11FB7A" authorityName="K.Morimoto" authorityYear="1962" baseAuthorityName="Morimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1962" box="[1259,1436,1226,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudohylobius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9CA7FB2DFA11FB7A" box="[1259,1436,1226,1252]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Pseudohylobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the antennal funiculus consists of seven segments and a broad short oval club, whereas the funiculus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9D7BFB09FA11FA96" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2021" box="[1335,1436,1262,1288]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Obhylius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9D7BFB09FA11FA96" box="[1335,1436,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Obhylius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
counts six segments with a more elongate-oval club whose rather elongate glabrous base might indicate the inclusion of the seventh segment (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9991FAD1FD92FACE" box="[477,543,1334,1360]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
H). 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9A07FAD1FD3DFACE" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2021" box="[587,688,1334,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Obhylius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9A07FAD1FD3DFACE" box="[587,688,1334,1360]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Obhylius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also shares characters with 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9BA4FAD1FBDAFACE" authorityName="W.Kirby" authorityYear="1837" box="[1000,1111,1334,1360]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hylobiini">Hylobiini</taxonomicName>
. The fringes of bristles along front (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9891FABDFE91FAEA" box="[221,284,1370,1396]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">
Fig. 
<date id="FFB5107CA029FB7B995DFABDFE91FAEA" box="[273,284,1370,1396]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">1</date>
</figureCitation>
I) and hind margins of the underside of the prothorax, the very prominent strongly uncinate apex of the tibiae, the shape of the tibiae itself, and the presence of a femoral tooth (
<figureCitation id="13302A39A029FB7B9BF5FA99FC76FA06" box="[953,1019,1406,1432]" captionStart="FIGS 1" captionStartId="1.[151,210,1909,1933]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetId="figure-17@1.[190,1397,179,1882]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGS 1A-K. Habitus, genitalia and details of the male holotype of Obhylius arboricola Germann gen. nov., sp. nov. A-C. – habitus dorsal, ventral and lateral. D. – dorso-lateral view on head and rostrum. E-F. – penis in ventral and lateral views (tegmen and part of apodemes of penis broken). G. – ventrites. H. – antennal funiculus. I. – fringe of characteristic flattened bristles at front margin of prothorax. J. – tooth on left profemur, outer side. K. – tooth on left metafemur, inner side (Photos: C. Germann)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4556746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4556746/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Figs 1</figureCitation>
J-K) are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9D7DFA99FA11FA06" authorityName="W.Kirby" authorityYear="1837" box="[1329,1436,1406,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hylobiini">Hylobiini</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B989CFA45FEB8FA22" authorityName="Germar" authorityYear="1817" box="[208,309,1442,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Hylobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B989CFA45FEB8FA22" box="[208,309,1442,1468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Hylobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), although these fringes consist of conspicuously flattened bristles in the case of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9C8DFA45FAABFA22" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2021" box="[1217,1318,1442,1468]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Obhylius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B97FEAAEA029FB7B9C8DFA45FAABFA22" box="[1217,1318,1442,1468]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">Obhylius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB436BCA029FB7B988BFA21FAF9FA7E" blockId="2.[151,1437,362,1504]" box="[199,1396,1478,1504]" pageId="2" pageNumber="569">
The new genus is placed in the more utilitarian than phylogenetically supported subtribe 
<taxonomicName id="4C0B4D3FA029FB7B9CE7FA21FAFDFA7E" authorityName="Morimoto" authorityYear="1962" box="[1195,1392,1478,1504]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Cotasteromimina">Cotasteromimina</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
